So Dr. Khalil is Associate Professor and Director of Translational

28
00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:43.360
Neuro-Oncology from the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center, and he's going to

29
00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:46.340
present his project, "A Targetable Metabolite Increases Neuronal

30
00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:50.250
Hyperexcitability in a Glioma Microenvironment and Directs

31
00:01:50.340 --> 00:01:50.980
Tumor Growth."

32
00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:54.880
Thank you very much. Thanks for having me.

33
00:01:55.100 --> 00:01:58.890
I'm excited to talk about the work we've been doing over the past couple of years

34
00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:03.900
identifying a targetable metabolite that increases

35
00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:07.540
neuronal activity and thus excitability in the glioma

36
00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:09.920
microenvironment, and we believe drives tumor growth.

37
00:02:10.539 --> 00:02:12.000
So we started with a bigger question.

38
00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:15.720
What metabolite signaling could drive high-grade gliomas that's

39
00:02:15.780 --> 00:02:19.240
independent of IDH mutations, independent of grade,

40
00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:23.800
and mutational status? And we did that by collecting

41
00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:28.240
91 neurosurgical samples in a row, prospectively.

42
00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:31.960
And this was the idea that we could grab high-grade gliomas,

43
00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:33.000
low-grade gliomas,

44
00:02:33.980 --> 00:02:37.920
metastases, and normal brain, and be able to run a multi-omics approach, but

45
00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:40.060
focusing on unbiased metabolomics.

46
00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:44.020
And we evaluated 563 different metabolites, and

47
00:02:44.180 --> 00:02:44.680
of those,

48
00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:49.250
the one that was most remarkable and most overabundant was guanosine

49
00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:52.620
acetate, and I'm going to refer to that as GAA throughout the talk.

50
00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:53.520
And

51
00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:57.440
this is an intermediate in the creatine synthesis pathway.

52
00:02:57.960 --> 00:03:00.960
So as we looked at it, the first question is always, is this

53
00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:04.720
a function of cell turnover? These gliomas are very busy.

54
00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:07.680
Are they just creating lots of cellular architecture?

55
00:03:07.780 --> 00:03:11.600
But if you look at these peak intensities, you'll see that GAA was increased

56
00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:15.530
relative to high-grade glioma, low-grade glioma, and brain, while

57
00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:18.100
creatine, phosphocreatine, and creatinine were all

58
00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:22.640
mostly the same, indicating that this was accumulation that was

59
00:03:22.680 --> 00:03:24.120
differential from the pathway.

60
00:03:25.280 --> 00:03:29.260
And that as we continued to work through this, we validated this with two

61
00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:30.780
additional independent cohorts.

62
00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:35.600
And then if you look at the ability to discriminate between tissues on the

63
00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:37.840
basis of GAA, you can see that GAA

64
00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:42.640
is increased in high-grade glioma versus brain, and then again in high-grade

65
00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:46.480
glioma versus low-grade glioma with true positive rates that are

66
00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:50.060
quite high. We took an approach towards stable

67
00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:54.080
isotope tracing here, which helped us identify this was truly

68
00:03:54.140 --> 00:03:57.800
a bottleneck, and you can see here that in TS516

69
00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:01.829
glioma stem cells, in comparison to NHAs, you have contributions of fractional

70
00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:02.540
enrichment of

71
00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:07.620
GAA, but not creatine. And that as you accumulate

72
00:04:07.700 --> 00:04:11.520
GAA, this appears to be driven by an imbalance in AGAT and

73
00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:15.370
GAMT, which is highly correlated to glioma grade, and

74
00:04:15.420 --> 00:04:18.950
AGAT being upstream and GAMT being downstream of

75
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:19.601
GAA.

76
00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:24.600
We looked at this in vitro, and in vitro, you can see there's a variety of cell

77
00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:28.300
lines, both IDH mutant glioma stem cells and IDH wild-type glioma stem

78
00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:30.180
cells. All of them have variable

79
00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:34.980
secretion of GAA into the media, but it's very

80
00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:35.730
clear that

81
00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:40.020
neural stem cells and normal human astrocytes do not.

82
00:04:40.220 --> 00:04:44.200
We also looked at a neurosurgical approach and tried to use our

83
00:04:44.260 --> 00:04:47.530
ability to spatially evaluate these lesions

84
00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:52.120
and actually generated organoids from neurosurgical resections, and

85
00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:53.920
you can see the stereotactic images here.

86
00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:58.040
But basically, we were able to demonstrate that these organoids

87
00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:00.300
secreted GAA into the media

88
00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:04.740
in a ratio that was quite high in comparison to normal brain.

89
00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:08.480
And we further expanded that by looking at a series of cases where we could

90
00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:09.600
spatially resolve

91
00:05:10.580 --> 00:05:13.400
where high-grade glioma cells actually existed.

92
00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:17.140
This is an IDH wild-type glioblastoma, but you can see that as you move

93
00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:20.800
closer to the tumor from where the surgical corridor is at

94
00:05:20.820 --> 00:05:24.020
entry, where there is normal cortex, the GAA

95
00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:28.620
is quite low. And as you move towards the margin or the flare, you have an

96
00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:32.480
increase in the number of tumor cells, and subsequently, you have an increase in

97
00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:35.320
GAA, and you can move all the way to the tumor.

98
00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:39.160
And all of this is the case with an increase in AGAT expression

99
00:05:39.340 --> 00:05:41.380
and a stable

100
00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:44.680
and non-significant difference in creatine.

101
00:05:45.660 --> 00:05:49.550
A genetic knockout demonstrated that as you knock out AGAT, you

102
00:05:49.550 --> 00:05:52.740
have an increase in overall survival of these mice.

103
00:05:52.780 --> 00:05:56.660
There's an increase in tumor GAA in the wild type compared to the knockout,

104
00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:58.640
and creatine, again, remains the same.

105
00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:01.140
When you abolish AGAT,

106
00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:05.820
GAA secretion is diminished, but that does not affect the cell fitness in

107
00:06:05.880 --> 00:06:08.640
vitro. So these cells are just fine. They grow normally in a dish.

108
00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:13.180
And foreshadowing a little bit to come, when you move these extracranially

109
00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:16.750
outside of the neural environment, they don't have any difference in growth rate in

110
00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:20.668
the subcutaneous flank.So what is the mechanism

111
00:06:20.708 --> 00:06:24.608
by which this is happening, given that there seems to be a differential

112
00:06:24.628 --> 00:06:28.267
effect of placing these cells in the brain versus in the systemic

113
00:06:30.248 --> 00:06:34.008
parts of the body? Well, GAA is not a random metabolite in the

114
00:06:34.068 --> 00:06:36.308
sense that there also is a correlate here.

115
00:06:36.808 --> 00:06:40.588
GAMT deficiency is an inborn error of metabolism that's quite

116
00:06:40.688 --> 00:06:44.548
rare. But when these patients present, what they present with is a

117
00:06:44.688 --> 00:06:48.558
massive accumulation of GAA, but their symptoms are driven by

118
00:06:48.588 --> 00:06:52.228
toxicity of GAA in the brain. So these patients

119
00:06:52.268 --> 00:06:56.188
present with intractable epilepsy, hypotonia, neurologic dysfunction.

120
00:06:56.228 --> 00:06:59.648
In some ways, they mirror the clinical presentation of patients with GBM.

121
00:07:00.748 --> 00:07:04.228
And this is actually an EEG. These patients have seizures.

122
00:07:04.248 --> 00:07:08.148
This is a patient who's seizing. And when you provide a GAA-lowering diet,

123
00:07:08.188 --> 00:07:11.788
which we'll come to in a minute, you actually see normalization of that EEG.

124
00:07:12.188 --> 00:07:15.988
And we know from a lot of our excellent collaborators, and partners in the field

125
00:07:16.048 --> 00:07:19.468
that elevated neural activity is observed in glioma and

126
00:07:19.508 --> 00:07:23.088
propagates growth. And we know from inborn errors of

127
00:07:23.128 --> 00:07:27.028
metabolism that GAMT deficiency also has a

128
00:07:27.068 --> 00:07:30.968
relationship with elevated GAA. So we looked back at our knockouts, and

129
00:07:31.008 --> 00:07:34.828
we found that in these situations, GAA actually

130
00:07:34.868 --> 00:07:37.628
reverses neuronal depletion, reverses neural

131
00:07:37.638 --> 00:07:40.248
excitability in the glioma microenvironment.

132
00:07:40.578 --> 00:07:44.148
And you can see here that there is an AGAT wild-type mouse in which

133
00:07:44.208 --> 00:07:46.888
c-Fos, which is an indicator of neural activation,

134
00:07:47.808 --> 00:07:51.558
is elevated in the peritumoral cortex and compared to the AGAT knockout.

135
00:07:52.128 --> 00:07:56.008
Similarly, when looking at vGlut1, which is a marker

136
00:07:56.068 --> 00:07:59.768
of neuron-glioma interaction, you see a substantial decrease, when

137
00:07:59.808 --> 00:08:03.088
AGAT is knocked out in comparison to AGAT wild-type cells.

138
00:08:03.638 --> 00:08:05.228
And you're going to have to hang with me here for a minute.

139
00:08:05.268 --> 00:08:09.128
We're taking a bit of a turn into cancer neuroscience. I hope it makes sense.

140
00:08:09.308 --> 00:08:13.228
I'm just a country neurosurgeon, so I try and move along with the flow.

141
00:08:13.768 --> 00:08:17.568
But what you'll see is that GAA and GABA actually have a very

142
00:08:17.688 --> 00:08:21.288
similar chemical structure. And there has been some work in the past that has

143
00:08:21.328 --> 00:08:25.118
evaluated GAA and why it causes neural excitability and

144
00:08:25.168 --> 00:08:27.518
epilepsy in patients who have GAMT deficiency.

145
00:08:28.038 --> 00:08:31.358
And what we found was that in a correlation to

146
00:08:31.908 --> 00:08:32.437
other studies,

147
00:08:33.448 --> 00:08:36.088
GAA appears to act at the GABA A receptor.

148
00:08:36.129 --> 00:08:39.749
So you can see here GAA is applied, and then

149
00:08:39.788 --> 00:08:43.509
gabazine is applied, which abrogates the effect of

150
00:08:43.788 --> 00:08:43.889
a

151
00:08:45.008 --> 00:08:48.698
large GABA A receptor-dependent outward current, which we see in these normal

152
00:08:48.888 --> 00:08:50.468
mouse hippocampal brain slices.

153
00:08:51.268 --> 00:08:51.428
Now,

154
00:08:52.408 --> 00:08:55.988
why is it that occurs? That seems to be a inhibitory

155
00:08:56.048 --> 00:08:57.668
mechanism when applying GAA.

156
00:08:58.628 --> 00:09:02.588
Well, in normal brain, that is a normal adult brain, chloride

157
00:09:02.628 --> 00:09:06.458
efflux is hyperpolarizing. And in those situations, KCC2,

158
00:09:06.508 --> 00:09:08.968
which modulates chloride, is actually normal.

159
00:09:09.268 --> 00:09:13.008
But in the glioma environment, KCC2 is down, which

160
00:09:13.068 --> 00:09:16.508
causes a chloride efflux, which is depolarizing.

161
00:09:16.888 --> 00:09:19.638
And as it turns out, this was also at the same time,

162
00:09:20.448 --> 00:09:24.428
work was being done by Michel Amanji's group, which demonstrated that in DMG, you

163
00:09:24.528 --> 00:09:28.497
actually had GABA agonism, which causes tumor proliferation in

164
00:09:28.528 --> 00:09:32.068
those patients. And so we've confirmed in our xenografts

165
00:09:32.128 --> 00:09:36.058
that KCC2 downregulation was occurring in our

166
00:09:36.348 --> 00:09:38.478
intratumoral and peritumoral areas where

167
00:09:39.428 --> 00:09:40.978
tumor-infiltrated brain was present.

168
00:09:41.688 --> 00:09:45.608
And then to evaluate that more specifically, we looked at a 3D microarray,

169
00:09:45.648 --> 00:09:46.028
which

170
00:09:46.868 --> 00:09:50.808
allows us to evaluate normalized spike rates across a whole brain slice.

171
00:09:51.088 --> 00:09:54.888
And we found that, as expected, when you apply GAA to tumor-infiltrated

172
00:09:54.968 --> 00:09:58.908
brain, that is where chloride is dysregulated, you end up with an increase in

173
00:09:58.948 --> 00:10:02.788
normalized spike rate. When you apply it to a non-infiltrated portion of

174
00:10:02.808 --> 00:10:06.008
brain, really nothing happens. Perhaps there's even some trend

175
00:10:06.048 --> 00:10:09.188
towards inhibition. But when you add

176
00:10:09.248 --> 00:10:12.808
CLP257 through this infusion, which is a KCC2

177
00:10:12.888 --> 00:10:16.728
agonist, which normalizes KCC2 in this situation, you have no

178
00:10:16.768 --> 00:10:19.128
effect of GAA when adding

179
00:10:20.168 --> 00:10:23.488
it to tumor-infiltrated brain, indicative of GAA inducing

180
00:10:23.528 --> 00:10:27.208
hyperexcitability, specifically in the glioma microenvironment in this dependent

181
00:10:27.268 --> 00:10:27.568
manner.

182
00:10:29.008 --> 00:10:32.768
With the help of some collaborators, we evaluated this, in an

183
00:10:32.808 --> 00:10:36.588
optogenetics model. So TS516 glioma stem cells were

184
00:10:36.668 --> 00:10:37.287
xenografted,

185
00:10:38.088 --> 00:10:41.788
in genetically modified mice, and then opto-stimulation was performed.

186
00:10:42.548 --> 00:10:45.728
And we were able to demonstrate that in AGAT

187
00:10:45.848 --> 00:10:49.748
wild-type cells, you've had an increase in proliferation index, whereas

188
00:10:49.788 --> 00:10:52.828
in AGAT knockout cells, that stimulation was not relevant.

189
00:10:53.888 --> 00:10:57.368
And I mentioned that in GAMT deficiency, dietary

190
00:10:57.408 --> 00:11:01.098
modification is critical. And the reason for that is because

191
00:11:01.508 --> 00:11:03.468
this is a metabolic pathway with overflow.

192
00:11:03.908 --> 00:11:07.848
So if you are able to restrict the upstream contribution and

193
00:11:07.928 --> 00:11:11.648
over-supplement the downstream contribution, you should be able to modulate the

194
00:11:11.668 --> 00:11:13.568
effect of the enzyme. And in this situation,

195
00:11:15.068 --> 00:11:18.488
these children are supplemented with high doses of ornithine and an

196
00:11:18.608 --> 00:11:22.208
arginine-restricted diet. And as a result, they can go from

197
00:11:22.248 --> 00:11:25.648
intractable epilepsy to a normalized EEG relatively quickly.

198
00:11:26.208 --> 00:11:29.628
So the next question being, what can we do to simulate that in a

199
00:11:29.688 --> 00:11:33.528
situation where we have an aberrant metabolism in a

200
00:11:33.568 --> 00:11:34.988
tumor model? And so we,

201
00:11:36.348 --> 00:11:40.208
again, xenografted TS516 glioma stem cells and provided these mice

202
00:11:40.268 --> 00:11:44.088
with either an overabundance of ornithine as well as an

203
00:11:44.108 --> 00:11:47.948
arginine restriction, and what we saw was that these survival

204
00:11:49.068 --> 00:11:52.748
benefits pretty much approach those of our genetic knockout.

205
00:11:53.038 --> 00:11:56.228
And similarly, GAA was reduced in the dietary group,

206
00:11:57.008 --> 00:12:00.508
but not in the normal group. And we also saw a decrease

207
00:12:00.988 --> 00:12:04.728
in proliferation at the margins of these tumors in

208
00:12:05.648 --> 00:12:09.448
mice who had high ornithine and arginine-restricted diets compared to a

209
00:12:09.548 --> 00:12:10.068
normal diet.

210
00:12:11.488 --> 00:12:14.988
So we are very shortly going to be enrolling into a surgical window of opportunity

211
00:12:15.048 --> 00:12:18.808
trial of modulation of GAA. So 12 patients will be enrolled

212
00:12:18.828 --> 00:12:22.737
prospectivelyThey will be supplemented with ornithine, and

213
00:12:22.788 --> 00:12:23.148
they will,

214
00:12:23.968 --> 00:12:27.348
on the advice of our dieticians, have a arginine restrictive

215
00:12:27.888 --> 00:12:30.548
diet, which is hard to be completely deficient, but restrictive

216
00:12:31.368 --> 00:12:35.288
diet three to five days before surgery, and then we'll be able to collect specimen

217
00:12:35.328 --> 00:12:39.148
and determine intraoperative stereotactic sampling of brain tumor tissue for

218
00:12:39.268 --> 00:12:42.728
direct quantification of GAA and other factors.

219
00:12:43.968 --> 00:12:45.548
Thank you. This was truly a labor of love.

220
00:12:45.648 --> 00:12:49.228
Many, many individuals here, including my longtime partner

221
00:12:49.688 --> 00:12:53.258
in crime, Dr. McBrayer, and Yi Zhao, who is here as well, one of the

222
00:12:53.308 --> 00:12:56.148
postdoctoral fellows in his lab. So thank you all very much.

223
00:13:02.668 --> 00:13:06.248
Hi, wonderful question. I have actually several questions.

224
00:13:06.328 --> 00:13:06.468
So,

225
00:13:07.688 --> 00:13:11.538
starting with, it's lower and low-grade gliomas, but is it different between

226
00:13:11.588 --> 00:13:14.108
IDH wild type and IDH mutant gliomas?

227
00:13:14.768 --> 00:13:18.297
That's a really good question. We found that there is no difference-

228
00:13:18.908 --> 00:13:19.168
Okay

229
00:13:19.228 --> 00:13:20.668
... between mutational status.

230
00:13:21.328 --> 00:13:21.808
What about

231
00:13:23.268 --> 00:13:26.848
have you done the experiments in an immunocompetent model where

232
00:13:27.068 --> 00:13:30.608
it's been shown that both L-arginine and potentially GABA have

233
00:13:30.768 --> 00:13:32.068
immunomodulatory effects?

234
00:13:32.688 --> 00:13:35.488
Yeah, that's a great point. We've thought about that. We haven't gotten there yet.

235
00:13:35.648 --> 00:13:37.008
But that's an excellent thought.

236
00:13:37.388 --> 00:13:41.368
And the last question is about this paper that came out last

237
00:13:41.448 --> 00:13:44.908
year, which showed that gabapentin use is potentially

238
00:13:45.668 --> 00:13:47.708
beneficial to patients with glioma.

239
00:13:47.808 --> 00:13:51.678
So how do you interpret that paper in the

240
00:13:51.748 --> 00:13:52.888
context of your findings?

241
00:13:53.068 --> 00:13:56.768
Yeah, great question. There are a number of papers that date back

242
00:13:56.828 --> 00:14:00.708
